==Records== {{Refimprove|date=October 2013}} Despite the relative stasis of the Maltese climate, historical records present some variations. In the capital city of Valletta, meteorological officials of the time recorded a temperature of {{convert|1.2|°C|°F|abbr=on}} on 19 February 1895, which remains a record for the city.<ref name=Mifsud>{{Cite book |author=Dr. Charles Mifsud| title=The Climate of the Maltese Islands |publisher=Mireva Publication |year=1985}}</ref>
Regarding the island as a whole, a temperature of {{convert|-1.7|°C|°F|abbr=on}} was recorded on 1 February 1962, at Ta' Qali airfield, in the centre of the island, which was accompanied by frozen precipitation ([[hail]]), and later in the day covered by snowfall that lasted through the night, though this temperature is not recognised by the Malta Met Office as it was not an official recording station and didn't use worldwide meteorological standard instruments.<ref name=Mifsud />
Snow is a very rare phenomenon, although the island recorded several snow events since 1850, being the last one in 2014.<ref>https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20141231/local/updated-snowflakes-reported-in-several-parts-of-malta-met-office.550143</ref> There was a big snowfall in January 1858 (widespread snowfall), March 1877 (light snow without accumulation), February 1895 (snow squalls without accumulation), January 1905 (flurries without accumulation), March 1949 (snow recorded in the interior of the island), and 31 January 1962,<ref name=Mifsud /> On 31 December 2014 snow was reported at various locations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20141231/local/updated-snowflakes-reported-in-several-parts-of-malta-met-office-monitoring-situation.550143 |title=Updated - 'Snowflakes' reported in several parts of Malta - Met Office 'monitoring' situation |publisher=Timesofmalta.com |date=2014-12-31 |accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>. [[Graupel]] was also recorded during that day. That Winter went on to be one of the coldest and stormiest ever experienced in the Maltese Islands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weather.maltairport.com/en/weather-news/news/222/last-maltese-winter-one-of-the-stormiest-in-20-years.htm |title=Last Maltese winter one of the stormiest in 20 years &#124; Malta Weather - Malta Airport Met Office |publisher=Weather.maltairport.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/48139/december_brought_snow_pellets_and_record_low_temperatures |title=December brought snow pellets and record low temperatures |publisher=MaltaToday.com.mt |date=2015-01-07 |accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>
The lowest temperature ever recorded at Luqa International Airport was in January 1981, with {{Convert|1.4|°C|°F|1}}, and the highest temperature was {{Convert|43.8|°C|°F|1}}<ref name=NSO>{{cite web | last1 = Galdies | first1 = Charles | url = http://www.nso.gov.mt/statdoc/document_file.aspx?id=3141 | title = The Climate of Malta: statistics, trends, and analysis 1951-2010 | pages = 6–7 | year = 2011 | publisher = National Statistics Office | accessdate = 26 February 2013}}</ref> recorded in August 1999.
Among all countries in the world, Malta recorded the [[List of weather records#Lowest temperatures ever recorded|5th highest temperature]]: {{convert|1.4|°C|°F|abbr=on}} (after tropical [[Malaysia]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[Philippines]]) among lowest temperatures ever recorded
