{{Infobox fictional location | name = Ernest Legouve Reef | colour = #C0C0C0 | image = Wachusett Bank.png | imagesize = 250px | caption = Ernest Legouve Rock on 1921 Pacific map | source = | creator = Ernest‑Legouvé | type = [[Phantom island]] }} {{Location map |Pacific Ocean |label=Ernest Legouve Reef |lon_dir=W |lat_dir=S |lat_deg=35|lat_min=12 |lon_deg=150|lon_min=40 |position=right |width=300 |float=right |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg |marksize=20 |caption=Alleged location of Ernest Legouve Reef in the Pacific Ocean }} Located in the South Pacific (south of French [[Tuamotus|Tuamotu Islands]] and east of [[New Zealand]]), the '''Ernest Legouve Reef''' was reported in 1902 by the unnamed captain of the French ship ''Ernest‑Legouvé''. The reef was about 100 metres long and another reef was sighted near it.<ref>{{cite book |author=United States Hydrographic Office |title=Pacific Islands Pilot, v. 2 |publisher=Government Printing Office |location=Washington, D.C. |year=1916 |isbn= |page=56 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IHUwAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA56 |accessdate=2011-09-26 }}</ref> The reef was recorded in ''Paris Notice to Mariners'' 164/1122/1902, and the [[International Hydrographic Bureau]] stated it on February 9, 1957 giving an estimated position of {{coord|35|12|S|150|40|W|}}. It was searched for in 1982 and 1983 but not found, leading to it being considered a [[phantom island]]. Nevertheless, it is marked in the 2015 edition of the ''National Geographic Atlas of the World''.<ref>{{cite book |title=National Geographic Atlas of the World |edition=10th |year=2015 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=National Geographic |page=plate 109 |isbn=1-4262-1354-9}}</ref>
Other nearby historically reported reefs which appear to not exist include [[Wachusett Reef]], [[Jupiter Reef]] and [[Maria Theresa Reef]].
In its location and description, the Ernest Legouve Reef corresponds to the rock that was said to be all that was left of [[The Mysterious Island|Lincoln Island]] at the end of [[Jules Verne]]'s ''[[The Mysterious Island]]''.
