{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = Shades of Grey: Glasgow 1956-86 | image = | image_size = | border = | caption = | alt = | author = [[Oscar Marzaroli]], [[William McIlvanney]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = | publisher = [[Mainstream Publishing]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = {{Start date|1987|12|31|df=y}} | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 223 | awards = | isbn = 9781851580477 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | preceded_by_quotation_marks = | followed_by = | followed_by_quotation_marks = | wikisource = }} '''''Shades of Grey: Glasgow, 1956-86''''' is a book of photographs by [[Oscar Marzaroli]] with an essay by [[William McIlvanney]].<ref name=Guardian_flynn>{{cite news|last=Flynn|first=Bob|title=Arts: The camera that captured a city - Oscar Marzaroli caught the soul of Glasgow / A tribute to a photographer of the people|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 January 1991}}</ref>
One of the photos from the book, a 1963 portrait of three young boys wearing their mother's high-heeled shoes playing in Kidson Street in the [[Gorbals]] area of [[Glasgow]], was in 2005 made into a bronze statue installed in Queen Elizabeth Square.<ref name=ET>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|title=Is that you in the heels?|newspaper=Evening Times (Glasgow)|date=14 April 2005}}</ref><ref name=HG>{{cite news|last=Puttick|first=Helen|title=Gorbals boys in high heels are cast in bronze|newspaper=The Herald (Glasgow)|date=14 April 2005}}</ref> The statue was unveiled in August 2008 by [[Nicola Sturgeon]], then Scotland's Deputy First Minister.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorbals boys strut their stuff again|newspaper=The Times|date=30 August 2008}}</ref>
